00:47:46.520 --> 00:47:48.330
But I do think so
that personal-- so

00:47:48.330 --> 00:47:52.270
what I have learned is
I do try to smile a lot.

00:47:52.270 --> 00:47:55.320
I mean, it's not
unnatural for me to smile.

00:47:55.320 --> 00:47:58.440
I think I'm probably
now more aware of that.

00:47:58.440 --> 00:48:00.940
And I also think,
maybe, that it also

00:48:00.940 --> 00:48:03.560
comes with a little bit more
confidence in age, also.

00:48:03.560 --> 00:48:06.520
Of just not feeling like
I have something to prove,

00:48:06.520 --> 00:48:10.110
so maybe I'm not coming in
like, the bull in the china

00:48:10.110 --> 00:48:14.300
store type of thing, that I'm
a little bit softer as I even

00:48:14.300 --> 00:48:16.220
speak.

00:48:16.220 --> 00:48:16.950
Yeah, I do.

00:48:16.950 --> 00:48:20.890
I am hyper aware
of how I present.

00:48:20.890 --> 00:48:23.890
And so my advice
to you is smile.

00:48:23.890 --> 00:48:26.900
Smile, warmth, and then
say what you need to say.

00:48:26.900 --> 00:48:30.160
Be smart, and never hedge on
being smart, as none of us

00:48:30.160 --> 00:48:31.910
would do, I'm sure.

00:48:31.910 --> 00:48:34.600
But you know, you
want to come across

00:48:34.600 --> 00:48:36.100
and make your points clear.

00:48:36.100 --> 00:48:37.820
There was something
else that I didn't

00:48:37.820 --> 00:48:38.760
mention when I was talking.

00:48:38.760 --> 00:48:40.160
And I think it's actually
really interesting.

00:48:40.160 --> 00:48:41.760
And it goes to sort
of the solidarity

00:48:41.760 --> 00:48:44.010
of the sisterhood, and this
networking, and the change

00:48:44.010 --> 00:48:44.677
that I'm seeing.

00:48:44.677 --> 00:48:46.843
And I write about, and it's
called the amplification

00:48:46.843 --> 00:48:47.410
effect.

00:48:47.410 --> 00:48:48.590
Have you all heard of this?

00:48:48.590 --> 00:48:50.370
Yeah, yeah, right on.

00:48:50.370 --> 00:48:52.480
So for those who
don't know, I had

00:48:52.480 --> 00:48:55.590
read about this in
"The Washington Post"

00:48:55.590 --> 00:48:57.640
that the women in
the Obama White House

00:48:57.640 --> 00:49:00.270
realized very early
in the administration

00:49:00.270 --> 00:49:03.470
that they were being ignored.

00:49:03.470 --> 00:49:05.460
They were ignored
by the president,

00:49:05.460 --> 00:49:07.540
and by pretty much
everyone in the West Wing.

00:49:07.540 --> 00:49:11.160
And they'd come into meetings
and the president never

00:49:11.160 --> 00:49:14.260
called on them for questions or
for their thoughts or anything

00:49:14.260 --> 00:49:15.430
like that.

00:49:15.430 --> 00:49:18.130
Or, if they did
speak up, their ideas

00:49:18.130 --> 00:49:20.450
were being usurped by
the guy in the room.

00:49:20.450 --> 00:49:21.090
You know?

00:49:21.090 --> 00:49:23.256
So they made a point, and
all of a sudden, you know,

00:49:23.256 --> 00:49:24.800
like, John is owning that point.

00:49:24.800 --> 00:49:27.250
So they got together,
and they realized

00:49:27.250 --> 00:49:29.510
that they needed to do
something about this,

00:49:29.510 --> 00:49:32.870
and that they were going to
amplify each other's messages.

00:49:32.870 --> 00:49:35.270
So if Yas said something
brilliant in a meeting

00:49:35.270 --> 00:49:38.370
with the president,
as I'm sure she has,

00:49:38.370 --> 00:49:41.330
I would then say, you
know, as Yas said earlier.

00:49:41.330 --> 00:49:44.500
And now the point is
being owned by Yas.

00:49:44.500 --> 00:49:45.631
I'm emphasizing that.

00:49:45.631 --> 00:49:47.630
The president's looking
over at Yasmin like, oh,

00:49:47.630 --> 00:49:50.350
yeah, smart lady, good point.

00:49:50.350 --> 00:49:51.950
And they started doing that.

00:49:51.950 --> 00:49:54.580
They started making sure that
they were calling on each other

00:49:54.580 --> 00:49:57.670
and reinforcing the comments to
make sure that the guys weren't

00:49:57.670 --> 00:49:59.280
stealing any of these ideas.

00:49:59.280 --> 00:50:01.100
But something
interesting happened,

00:50:01.100 --> 00:50:04.820
which was that President Obama
started calling on the women

00:50:04.820 --> 00:50:05.320
more.

00:50:05.320 --> 00:50:07.080
Started inviting them
to more meetings.

00:50:07.080 --> 00:50:08.130
They were visible.

00:50:08.130 --> 00:50:10.290
They made themselves visible.

00:50:10.290 --> 00:50:12.940
So this whole concept
of amplifying each other

00:50:12.940 --> 00:50:14.000
is really important.

00:50:14.000 --> 00:50:16.810
And certainly not just in the
West Wing, but in the work

00:50:16.810 --> 00:50:17.620
space, right?

00:50:17.620 --> 00:50:19.240
We need to be
supporting each other.

00:50:19.240 --> 00:50:22.150
We need to be recognizing
what we're saying,

00:50:22.150 --> 00:50:23.740
what our contributions are.

00:50:23.740 --> 00:50:25.660
And it's really,
really helpful to have

00:50:25.660 --> 00:50:28.810
someone else do that for you.

00:50:28.810 --> 00:50:32.522
I don't know if anyone here
read Jessica Bennett's book,

00:50:32.522 --> 00:50:34.230
and I'm going to screw
up the name-- it's

00:50:34.230 --> 00:50:36.880
"The Feminist Fight
Club" is her book,

00:50:36.880 --> 00:50:38.600
and which is a great read.

00:50:38.600 --> 00:50:41.790
And she writes about
having a boast bitch.

00:50:41.790 --> 00:50:43.872
And that boast bitch
is someone who--

00:50:43.872 --> 00:50:45.580
by the way, it could
be your best friend,

00:50:45.580 --> 00:50:46.955
it could be your
mother, it could

00:50:46.955 --> 00:50:49.660
be your sister-- it's having
someone be able to amplify

00:50:49.660 --> 00:50:50.700
messages for you.

00:50:50.700 --> 00:50:53.300
And I'm sure there's
tons of studies on,

00:50:53.300 --> 00:50:55.890
with Facebook likes, and
Instagram likes, and you know,

00:50:55.890 --> 00:50:58.360
what gets the most likes
and all this kind of stuff.

00:50:58.360 --> 00:51:01.060
But there's something to be
said, when someone else says

00:51:01.060 --> 00:51:03.410
something about you, or
someone posts something like,

00:51:03.410 --> 00:51:06.440
oh, I'm so proud of my wife--

00:51:06.440 --> 00:51:08.940
her book was published--

00:51:08.940 --> 00:51:11.570
that tends to get more likes
than if I actually put out,

00:51:11.570 --> 00:51:13.410
hey, my book was published.

00:51:13.410 --> 00:51:15.115
So it's the same
sort of concept.

00:51:15.115 --> 00:51:16.960
So you have someone else.

00:51:16.960 --> 00:51:20.180
You have someone who's
amplifying the great work

00:51:20.180 --> 00:51:21.690
that you're doing
in the workplace.

00:51:21.690 --> 00:51:23.820
And having that boast
bitch is really effective.

00:51:23.820 --> 00:51:26.220
First of all, I
just love the idea,

00:51:26.220 --> 00:51:29.000
and I think it's very empowering
and very much as a sisterhood

00:51:29.000 --> 00:51:32.200
that we need to be
supporting each other.

